value.value: The male genitalia muscle that originates from the parossiculus and inserts on the endophallic membrane around the phallotrema.
The sclerite that is connected via conjunctiva distomedially to the gonostipes, and articulates with the gonossiculus.
The area that is round and differs from surrounding regions in sculpture, setae, and/or pigmentation.
The sclerite that is located ventrally of the thoracic segment and bears the furca and the lateral coxal condyle of the pleuron.
The antennal segment that is connected proximally to the scape and distally to the flagellum.
The sclerite that is in the middle of the external male genitalia, surrounds the distal part of the ductus ejaculatorius and the endophallus.
The male genitalia muscle that arises from the medial surface of the proximal part of the penisvalva and inserts on the endophallus just around the phallotrema.
The anatomical cluster that comprises the ventral marginal of the cranium, including the clypeus, the pleurostomata, and the hyperstomata.
A sclerotic ring surrounding the outer spiracular opening.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the cupulae, gonostipites and volsellae.
The anatomical space that is the distal opening of the endophallus.
The developing adult after pupal-adult apolysis, i.e. from stage P8 (when yellow eye color first becomes visible through the pupal case), to eclosion.
The antecosta that corresponds to the site of attachment of the dorsal longitudinal muscles in the thorax.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of fine, dense setae, acanthae or microtrichiae.
The patch that is impressed and corresponds to an apophysis.
The sclerite that is located proximoventrally on the pretarsus and is connected proximally with the unguitractor plate and distally with the arolium.
The apodeme that is located on the pleuron.
The apophysis that is adjacent to the pleural ridge.
The anatomical cluster composed of the pro-, meso-, and metapleura.
The pit that is located on the pleuron and corresponds to the pleural apophysis.
The ridge that extends between the pleural wing process and the lateral coxal articulation and marks the border between the episternum and epimeron.
The sulcus that corresponds to the pleural ridge and separates the episternum from the epimeron.
The fossa that is located on the dorsal margin of the pleuron and accommodates the second axillary sclerite.
The sclerite that is located on the pleuron.
The line of separation between the pleural region and the venter, lying mesad of the limb bases, but obscured when the latter are fused with the sterna.
The sclerite that articulates with the leg and is connected along its dorsal margin with the notum and ventral margin with the sternum.

The area that extends on the ventral (anterior) margin of the cranium along the site of origin of the conjunctiva connecting the mandible with the cranium and is delimited posteriorly (ventrally) by the posterior (ventral) margin of the pleurostomal fossa and anteriorly (dorsally) by the anterior (dorsal) margin of the pleurostomal condyle and laterally by the mouth margin.
The condyle that is located on the anterior (dorsal) margin of the pleurostoma and inserts into the mandibular acetabulum.
The fossa that is located postero- (ventro-) medially on the pleurostoma and accommodates the mandibular condyle.
The ridge that extends between the pleurostomal fossa and pleurostomal condyle and delimits the lateral margin of the pleurostoma.
The suture that is dorsal to the mandible and is part of the subgenal suture.
The carina that arises from the anterior margin of the abdominal tergum 1 medially of the propodeal spiracle extends to the posterior propodeal projection.
The wing fold that is located between the mediocubital field and axillary region.
The wing fold that is located between the cubital field and the first vannal vein.
The area that is delimited laterally by the metapleural carina and medially by the plica.
The area corresponding to the upper margin of the mandible, above the acetabular groove, commonly ending in the preapical tooth or teeth.
The setiferous patch that is located ventrally on the mesopleuron posterior to the epicnemial carina.
The sulcus that extends posteriorly along the epicnemial carina.
The process that is located anterolaterally on the mesoscutellar-axillar complex and separates the site of origin of the fore wing from the site of origin of the hind wing.
The area that is located on the clypeus and is delimited by the epistomal sulcus and a medial transverse anatomical line.
The usual sixth vein of the wing, associated basally with the cubitus.
The mandibular muscle that arises posterodorsally from the cranium and inserts on the tendon attached anteroproximally on the mandible.
The area that is located on the posteroventral corner of the preaxilla and articulates with the anterior extension of the lateral axillar area.

The area that is delimited laterally distally and proximally by the sclerites that are connected to the distal margin of the prementum and receive the site of insertion of the premento-paraglossal muscle.
The sclerite of the posterior glossal plate that is paired.
The labral muscle that arises from the upper face laterally to the anterior fronto-labral muscle and inserts on the torma.
The area that extends along the posterior margin of the mesopleuron and is delimited anteriorly by the mesepimeral sulcus.
The inflection that extends along the posterior margin of the mesepimeron, posteriorly of the subalar pit to the coxal articulation.
The mesolaterophragmal muscle that originates from the mesofurca and inserts on the mesolaterophragma posterior to the site of origin of the anterior mesofuco-mesolaterophragmal muscle.

The mesonoto-mesotrochanteral muscle that arises from the dorsal axillar area, posteriorly of the site of origin of the anterior mesonoto-mesotrochanteral muscle (if present) and inserts on the mesotrochanteral apodeme.
